<h3>Game Questions</h3>
<h4>Q: So what historical period is this system aimed at?</h4>
<p>
Horse and Musket period gaming.
</p>
<p>The original "Kriegsspeil" rules were written in 1824 by a Prussian Army officer based on his 1st hand experience in the Napoleonic Wars</p>
<p>Subsequent revisions by professional staff officers of the time include weapons data updates up to and including "the Age of Rifles", with data published for early needle guns and breech loading rifled artillery.</p>
<p>Whilst the data is there for a range of weapons, the purpose of the "Kriegsspeil" system was to train officers in the art of command, and not so much as a celebration of new battlefield technology. The real strength of the "Kriegsspiel" rules is the way that it models the interaction between the 3 arms (Infantry / Cavalry / Artillery), and more or less <i>demands</i> that the player plan ahead and coordinate their forces properly ... or face the consequences.</p>
<p>So in summary - perfect for the Napoleonic Period, suitable for earlier Linear Warfare such as 7YW, generally useful for ACW, Crimea, FPW and possibly useful up to the end of the 19th Century and into WW1, depending on the campaign.</p>
<p>Do note however, using a computer AT ALL in a wargame does change the "feel" of the gameplay, and you may need to consider this. Whilst it might produce fast and accurate results, for say ... a Colonial Period Wargame set in the unknown depths of Darkest Africa, it might also introduce a disgracefully sterile feel for a gathering of Gentlemen, chuffing on pipes and sipping brandy near an open fireplace, whilst planning how they should hold the city from the coming invasion.</p>

<hr>
<h4>Q: I get enough of Computers at work - I prefer Dice for my gaming thank you.</h4>
<p>I understand this, and agree.</p>
<p>This is indeed a "game" or "simulation" of War, in which the player must constantly make critical life and death decisions, and then accept the results of things that he has little or no control over. Sounds like rolling dice !</p>
<p>Player involvement (even if its just rolling a dice and passively suffering the consequences of the roll), is actually of critical importance to capturing the gravity of the situation being modelled on the tabletop, and have the player understand the process involved that produces that consequent effect.<p>
<p>The system aims to be transparent in the mechanics that are used, so this includes displaying the odds of success for each choice the player makes ... and finally, <i>Requiring the Player to ROLL THE DICE</i> to get a result. This keeps everyone involved in the action, and allows every player to understand WHY things are happening on the tabletop as they happen.</p>

<hr>
<h4>Q: What ? Computer moderated with Dice - How does that possibly work?</h4>
<p>For each combat situation that occurs in the game, the computer asks a series of straight forward questions, and then presents the commanding player with a set of choices to make, and roughly what the odds of success of each choice are.</p>
<p>The defending player in this combat situation must answer the same questions, and may also be asked to decide on a reaction choice to make to counter the commanding player's move.</p>
<p>Once all the inputs for the situation are entered by BOTH players, the Computer Umpire generates a simple table of results from a D6, and shows this results table to BOTH affected players.</p>
<p>The commanding player rolls the dice. Both players then click the appropriate number that matches the die roll, (and when both the inputs agree), the results are applied.</p>

<hr>
<h4>Q: So its up to the players to negotiate with each other over each combat situation?</h4>
<p>Correct.</p>
<p>The basic "straight forward questions" are simple factors that both players should be able to agree on, but tabletop games are by their nature analog affairs, where much is open to interpretation, imagination, experience, and negotiation. </p>
<p>These factors are indeed what makes tabletop gaming unique and appealing compared to computer games, so this system attempts to embrace that rather than replace it.</p>
<p>It also means that player involvement is kept high throughout the game, and that all players are given every opportunity to understand the mechanics involved, and argue their case to influence those odds. 
<p>The sort of situational factors that affect each combat situation include obvious questions such as :</p>
<ul>
	<li>Range between opposing units?</li>
	<li>Is the terrain in question Open / Rough / Wooded?</li>
	<li>Is the target under cover?</li>
	<li>Hit in the Flank ?</li>
</ul>
<p>.. which are all straight forward, through to other questions which may be more open to negotiation, and may require the players to state a strong case for applying them or not :</p>
<ul>
	<li>Has a supporting line to the rear within reach should they need to retreat ?</li>
	<li>Is this artillery firing to good effect, or is it obscured ?</li>
	<li>Should the defending unit be considered suprised and ambushed by this attack ?</li>
	<li>.. etc</li>
</ul>
<p>All up, there are over 1,000 possible combinations of Unit vs Unit combat situations included in the game model, each with a variety of modifying factors that can influence the result.</p>

<hr>
<h4>Q: What's the detail of the Combat Results ?</h4>
<p>Combat results are computed and presented on 3 separate levels, so lets look at that in more detail.</p>
<ol>
	<li>General Outcome.
	<p>Whenever 2 opposing units clash, there are 6 general outcomes, all things considered:</p>
	<ol>
		<li>Attacker Wins, Defender Totally Defeated</li>
		<li>Attacker Wins, Defender Defeated</li>
		<li>Attacker Wins, Defender Repulsed</li>
		<li>Attacker Repulsed</li>
		<li>Attacker Defeated</li>
		<li>Attacker Totally Defeated</li>
	</ol>
	<p>So when opposing units engage, they fight, and then all players are informed of the General Outcome of each encounter. The calculation of the odds of each outcome though is somewhat complicated, and needs a whole book to explain. The Computer backend manages to look after the details of these calculations for you.</p>
	<p>Each unit that is involved in a contact - whether it wins or loses, will have actual casualties calulated and applied based on the situation and the general result.</p>
	</li>
	<li>Logistical Data.
	<p>Each individual unit on the table is tracked in detail, including :</p>
	<ul>
		<li>Exact number of actual men in the unit.</li>
		<li>Exact number of wounded / killed / sick / panicked.</li>
		<li>Ammunition and supply state.</li>
		<li>Fatigue state.</li>
		<li>Command & Control state.</li>
	</ul>
	<p>All of these factors are both linear and deterministic, so that over the course of a battle they degrade at a predictable rate as they take fire and get involved in combats.</p>
	<p>Attrition due to casualties is tracked by the computer umpire, and does not require any figure or base removal.</p>
	<p>Each time a unit receives fire (from musket / skirmisher / artillery), individual casualties are computed and applied for each unit.</p>
	<p>Each time a unit fires, ammunition and supply state is computed and applied.</p>
	<p>Each time a unit moves, changes formation, or performs some other physical action, fatigue and control costs are computed and applied to the unit.</p>
	<p>Each time a unit spends a period recovering, fatigue / control state and supply state recovery is computed and applied to the unit.</p>
	<p>During the course of a game, a player can move (the command base representing themselves) to a unit, and "Perform an Inspection", to gain access to the detailed logistical state of the unit they are inspecting.</p>
	<p>Unless the unit is being personally inspected by the player, these logistical details are not available during the game.</p>
	<p>At the end of the game, all logistical details for all units of all sides are available.</p>
	</li>
	<li>Morale State
	<p>Morale is modelled using the following general principles :</p>
	<ul>
		<li>It is assumed that all units and sub-commands will have a very limited understanding of the overall situation on the tabletop, and can only act based on what is happening in their immediate local area.</li>
		<li>As a general rule, units and sub-commands will act in strict accordance with their orders, and continue to do so until the unit completely breaks.</li>
		<li>That negative changes in the morale state can occur suddenly, are hard to predict, and sometimes hard to explain or justify - but they do happen, and they can happen to any unit on any side involved.</li>
		<li>That casualty levels due to attrition do not have a serious impact on morale state. Loss of morale is more related to unexpected "shock" from exceptional events - either real or imagined.</li>
		<li>That morale state recovery during the course of a game is much slower and more predictable than morale loss.</li>
	</ul>
		
	</li>

</ol>


